explanation:
List of required symbols and why they are needed to decide if the target function contains dead code:

1. UT_GetStubEntry
   - The function's control flow and whether the first/second branches execute depends on the return behavior and side-effects of UT_GetStubEntry (when it can return NULL vs non-NULL, whether it may allocate/claim an entry). Necessary to determine if any branch is never taken (dead).

2. UT_ENTRYTYPE_CALLBACK_CONTEXT
   - The enum/macro value passed to UT_GetStubEntry. Knowing its meaning is required to reason about which entry is being searched and whether that search can succeed, affecting reachability of subsequent assignments.

3. UT_ENTRYTYPE_UNUSED
   - The alternate enum/macro value used in the second UT_GetStubEntry call. Must be known to determine whether the second search can ever succeed and thereby whether the first-call-failed path and remainder of the function are executed.

4. UT_StubTableEntry_t
   - The struct layout (fields used: FuncKey, EntryType, Data.Context.ArgCount, Data.Context.ArgPtr[], Data.Context.Meta[]) is needed to assess whether writes performed by this function have any effect on program behavior and whether any written fields are unused (i.e., dead writes).

5. UT_StubArgMetaData_t
   - The struct layout (fields used: Name, Size, Type) is required to analyze the pointer manipulations and type assignments in the Name-processing loop and to see whether modifying MetaPtr->Name is well-defined and has an observable effect.

6. UT_STUBCONTEXT_MAXSIZE
   - The numeric limit compared to ArgCount controls whether the block that stores ParamPtr/Meta is ever executed. If ArgCount is always >= this constant then the whole storing block would be dead; its value/semantics are required.

7. UT_STUBCONTEXT_ARG_TYPE_UNSPECIFIED
8. UT_STUBCONTEXT_ARG_TYPE_INDIRECT
9. UT_STUBCONTEXT_ARG_TYPE_DIRECT
   - These constants control the conditional logic that sets MetaPtr->Type. Their definitions and possible initial values are needed to determine if the conditional assignments change observable state, or if they are redundant (dead assignments).

10. UtAssert_Abort
   - The behavior of this function (particularly whether it is non-returning and whether it has externally visible side-effects) is essential to judge whether the abort call is required for correct program behavior or whether it could be removed without effect (i.e., dead). Also determines reachability of the else branch when StubPtr==NULL.

11. UT_MAX_FUNC_STUBS
   - Mentioned in the abort message and related to the capacity of the stub table. Knowing this value/context helps determine whether the error condition is ever reachable in normal operation and whether the abort branch is meaningful vs effectively dead.

Note: to fully assess the MISRA dead-code rule, the analyzer will need the runtime semantics (return conditions and side-effects) of the above symbols (especially UT_GetStubEntry and UtAssert_Abort) and the concrete sizes/limits and struct layouts so it can decide if particular assignments/branches are ever executed or ever affect observable program state.
